value.value: Condyloma acuminatum that is associated with the presence of dysplastic epithelial changes.
A congenital mesoblastic nephroma characterized by the presence of classic and cellular areas.
A cystic dilatation that occurs in any part of the biliary tree.
A cyst lined by tissue that resembles synovial villi.
A rare congenital malformation in the larynx. It is characterized by the presence of an air-filled sac within the laryngeal wall which may bulge on the neck.
A cystic structure located between the ovary and fallopian tube.
An idiopathic disorder characterized by the degeneration of the aortic media tissue and formation of cyst-like spaces. It may lead to aortic dissection.

A reactive, benign fibrous lesion that develops in the periosteum of the femur.  It usually affects boys and there is a history of trauma.  It is characterized by the formation of dense collagen tissue and reactive bone.
An acute inflammatory process affecting the esophageal wall.
A chronic inflammatory process affecting the esophageal wall.
Extramedullary hematopoiesis occurring during adulthood.
A congenital disorder characterized by blockage or absence of the extrahepatic bile ducts.
A congenital disorder characterized by blockage or absence of the intrahepatic bile ducts.

A congenital disorder usually inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern. It affects the hepatobiliary system and the kidneys. It is characterized by liver fibrosis, portal hypertension, and renal cysts.
A congenital disorder of the intrahepatic bile ducts characterized by abnormal embryonal development of the ductal plates.
An inherited disorder characterized by progressive degeneration and atrophy of the nervous system.
An autosomal dominant inherited disorder characterized by the presence of smaller than normal, sphere-shaped erythrocytes. It results in hemolytic anemia and splenomegaly.
An inherited genetic disorder that affects the connective tissues. Representative examples include Ehlers-Danlos syndrome and Marfan syndrome.

A rare, slow-growing, locally aggressive soft tissue tumor characterized by the presence of oval to spindle cells forming concentric aggregates around small vessels.  Giant multinucleated cells are also present.

An acute inflammation of the umbilical cord. It is characterized by the presence of polymorphonuclear cells migrating from the fetal umbilical cord vessels through the umbilical cord towards the bacteria containing amniotic fluid.
A non-neoplastic proliferation of lymphocytes in lymph nodes and/or extranodal sites.
Hyperplasia of the bronchial epithelial cells.  It is often associated with squamous metaplasia.
A benign fibrous hyperplasia in the oral mucosa caused by the prolonged wear of ill-fitting denture.
Hyperplasia characterized by the presence of a diffuse cellular infiltrate.
Overgrowth of the gingival tissue caused by phenytoin, cyclosporine A, and calcium channel blockers.
Hyperplasia characterized by the presence of a focal proliferation of epithelial cells.
Hyperplasia of the germinal centers resulting in the enlargement of the lymph node.
Inflammation of the aorta. Causes include trauma, infectious disorders, and connective tissue disorders.
The formation of stones (calculi) in the body.
Dilatation of the lymphatic vessels.

An inherited or acquired disorder that affects the metabolism of the carbohydrates. Representative examples include diabetes mellitus, glycogen storage disease, mucopolysaccharidoses, and lactose intolerance.
An inherited disorder that affects the metabolism of the amino acids. Representative examples include alkaptonuria, homocystinuria, tyrosinemia, and phenylketonuria.
An inborn metabolic disorder affecting the intermediary metabolism process. It results in accumulation of substances in the body that can cause acute or chronic intoxication.
An inherited metabolic disorder caused by an enzyme deficiency, resulting in an inability to oxidize fatty acids for energy production.
A congenital or acquired disorder characterized by abnormal loss or redistribution of the adipose tissue in the body.
A finding indicating the formation of calcium oxalate crystal deposits in an organ.
A metabolic disorder that affects the phosphate homeostasis.
A group of genetic or acquired metabolic disorders characterized by defects in the enzymes that are involved in the heme synthesis.

A reactive metaplastic change in the urinary tract epithelium.  The metaplastic changes in the epithelium resemble renal tubular structures.  It can occur following surgical procedures, inflammation, stone formation, or trauma.
A finding indicating the presence of cadmium mineral deposits in an organ.
A genetic or acquired metabolic disorder that is associated with zinc deficiency in the tissues.

An iodinated doxorubicin analogue with antiamyloid activity. 4'-Iodo-4'-deoxydoxorubicin (IDOX) binds with high affinity to five types of natural amyloid fibrils including immunoglobulin light chains, amyloid A, transthyretin (methionine-30 variant), beta-protein (Alzheimer), and beta2-microglobulin. This agent may inhibit fibril growth, increasing the solubility of amyloid tissue deposits and facilitating their clearance. IDOX has also been shown to insulin amyloid fibrillogenesis in vitro.
A morphologic finding indicating the presence of enlarged muscle cells in a muscle tissue sample.
